    <title type="html"><![CDATA[Creating a Github Blog Using Octopress]]></title>
    <link href="http://www.metgher.com/blog/2013/10/10/creating-a-github-blog-using-octopress/"/>
    <updated>2013-10-10T20:40:00-04:00</updated>
    <id>http://www.metgher.com/blog/2013/10/10/creating-a-github-blog-using-octopress</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p style="text-align:center;"> <img src="http://www.metgher.com/images/octopress.png" title="octopress logo" alt="alt text" /></p>

<p>With <a href="http://octopress.org/">Octopress</a>, I write my blog posts in <a href="https://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/">Markdown</a>. Octopress uses uses <a href="https://github.com/jekyll/jekyll">Jekyll</a> that runs with <a href="http://pages.github.com/">Github pages</a>.</p>

<p>Markdown offers a clean and simple syntax for text formating, translates fast and easily to HTML. It&rsquo;s flexibility allows for outputing files into a wide array of formats, that are implicitly cross-platform.</p>

<p>Several third party Octopress themes are available <a href="https://github.com/imathis/octopress/wiki/3rd-Party-Octopress-Themes">here</a>. There are several resources to help you get started with Octopress, such as the following:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="http://kvz.io/blog/2012/09/25/blog-with-octopress/?utm_source=feedburner&amp;utm_medium=feed&amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+kvz+(Kevin+van+Zonneveld">Blog With Octopress and Github Pages</a>)</li>
<li><a href="http://tech.paulcz.net/2012/12/creating-a-github-pages-blog-with-octopress.html">Creating a Github Pages Blog With Octopress</a></li>
<li>Blogging With Octopress <a href="http://mattgemmell.com/blogging-with-octopress/">here</a> and <a href="http://mindthecode.com/blogging-with-octopress/">here</a></li>
</ul>


<p>The documentation on the <a href="http://octopress.org/">Octopress</a> is pretty good too. Enjoy!</p>
]]></content>
